<div class="prose">

<h2>What an AI Partner is</h2>

<p>An AI Partner is a purpose-built chat surface for one specific job in this course. They're not general-purpose chatbots — each one has a defined role, a tuned prompt, and a clear scope. Some are domain coaches (Plate Tectonics Tutor); some are process partners (Source Evaluator, Defense Practice). All of them are <strong>sources</strong>, and OPVL applies.</p>

<p>The five starter partners are documented on the <a href="/ai-partners/">AI Partners</a> page.</p>

<h2>The three rules</h2>

<ol>
  <li><strong>AI can help me think — but I do the thinking.</strong> If you couldn't defend an argument in conversation because the AI made it, that argument isn't yours.</li>
  <li><strong>The work I submit is my words, my decisions, my voice.</strong> Partners can support drafting; the deliverable is yours.</li>
  <li><strong>Every time I use AI, I document it.</strong> No exceptions. See the <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation Protocol</a>.</li>
</ol>

<h2>When to reach for a partner vs. a general AI</h2>

<table>
  <thead>
    <tr><th>Situation</th><th>Reach for…</th></tr>
  </thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Stuck on a Unit 3 concept (subduction, <a href="/reference/glossary/liquefaction/">liquefaction</a>, hazard signatures)</td><td><strong>Plate Tectonics Tutor</strong> — domain-tuned, less likely to drift.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Need to OPVL a source you're not sure about</td><td><strong>The Source Evaluator</strong> — walks you through OPVL on whatever you paste in.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Want to stress-test a claim or argument</td><td><strong>The Skeptic</strong> — pushes back. Especially useful before a defense.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Framing an engineering problem or weighing trade-offs</td><td><strong>Engineering Coach</strong> — for Unit 3 portfolio work and any sim decisions.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Rehearsing a defense or oral assessment</td><td><strong>Defense Practice Partner</strong> — asks the questions your panel might ask.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Need a translation, a different explanation, or general feedback</td><td>A general AI (Gemini, Claude, ChatGPT). Same documentation rules apply.</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Documentation, every time</h2>

<div class="callout warn">
  <div class="callout-title">No exceptions</div>
  Whether you used a course partner for two minutes or general Gemini for two hours, you fill out the <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Documentation Template</a>. Honest disclosure = no penalty. Hidden use = academic integrity violation.
</div>

<h2>What partners cannot do for you</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Decide what's true.</strong> Partners can explain mechanisms, surface options, give feedback. They cannot resolve a contested scientific question for you.</li>
  <li><strong>Write your work.</strong> If 80% of a paragraph came from a partner, it's the partner's work.</li>
  <li><strong>Replace evaluation.</strong> Every partner output is itself a source. OPVL applies. Watch especially for hallucinated citations, confident wrongness, and sycophancy — see the <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">protocol</a> for the failure modes to watch for.</li>
</ul>

<h2>If you're unsure</h2>

<blockquote>"Could I explain to my teacher exactly what I did, and would I be comfortable doing so?"</blockquote>

<p>If yes, document it and submit. If no, stop and recalibrate before submitting.</p>

</div>
